{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 13:29:06.431025", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — network health assessment\n\nSummary (executive)\n- The network control plane (FRR/OSPF across the core and distribution/router devices) appears healthy and converged: OSPF adjacencies are up and appropriate inter-area routes (including the server farm 10.200.0.0/24 and the user subnets 10.2.1.0/24 etc.) are present in the routing tables on core and distribution routers.\n- Data-plane reachability is inconsistent: some hosts and servers can reach each other, while at least one access host (host_2_1_1_1) cannot reach remote subnets (e.g., the web server 10.200.0.5). The failures are localized to host/network-edge configuration rather than to router OSPF/routing.\n- Primary abnormality: host netmask misconfiguration (host_2_1_1_1 shows a /8 mask instead of the expected /24), causing the host to treat remote subnets as \"local\" and fail to forward traffic via its gateway (resulting in local ARP failures / \"Destination Host Unreachable\").\n\nWhat I checked (actions and key outputs)\n1. Global reachability summary (aggregated ping sweep)\n   - Many pairwise checks included in the provided reachability matrix; some were successful (e.g., dns_server → web_server_2 ok), others unknown/incomplete. This suggested targeted testing was needed.\n\n2. OSPF / routing tables (parallel checks on routers)\n   - router_core_1, router_core_2, router_core_3, switch_dist_1_1, switch_dist_2_1, switch_server_access: each shows OSPF routes for the user subnets (10.1.x.x / 10.2.x.x) and the server subnet 10.200.0.0/24. Example: router_core_3 has O>* 10.200.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.15; other routers have routes to 10.2.1.0/24 and 10.2.2.0/24. OSPF process info shows healthy numbers of LSAs and Full adjacencies.\n   - OSPF neighbor state output: adjacencies are Full (DR/Backup/DR as expected) across the core and distribution links — no adjacency flaps or obvious router-level OSPF failures seen in the snapshots.\n\n3. Targeted pings\n   - host_1_1_1_1 → web_server_2 (10.200.0.5): 4/4 replies, rtt avg ~2.85 ms (successful).\n   - dns_server → host_1_1_1_1: 4/4 replies (successful).\n   - host_2_1_1_1 → web_server_2: returned \"From 10.2.1.2 icmp_seq=N Destination Host Unreachable\" for all attempts (4/4 failed). That ICMP error is sourced by 10.2.1.2 (the host itself).\n   - host_2_1_1_1 → other local hosts on 10.2.x: some pings to same-LAN hosts succeed (see aggregated results where other host-to-host inside 10.2.1.0/24 were OK).\n\n4. End-host network config (host_2_1_1_1)\n   - ifconfig / ip addr show:\n     - inet 10.2.1.2 netmask 255.0.0.0 (i.e., /8)\n     - default via 10.2.1.1 dev eth0\n     - route table shows 10.0.0.0/8 dev eth0 and default via 10.2.1.1\n   - This is the critical piece of evidence.\n\nDiagnosis — anomalies and localization\n- Anomaly: Host netmask misconfiguration on host_2_1_1_1 (and likely other hosts in that access subnet if deployed similarly). The host's IP is 10.2.1.2 with netmask 255.0.0.0 (/8). The network design expects per-access /24s (10.<core>.<dist>.0/24).\n- Localization: Problem localized to the access host(s) — specifically observed on host_2_1_1_1 (10.2.1.2). Router and OSPF-level checks show no routing anomalies affecting reachability to the server farm; routers have routes for 10.200.0.0/24 and for user subnets. Web servers and DNS are reachable from other parts of the network.\n- Root-cause indication: Because host_2_1_1_1 uses a /8 mask, it believes 10.200.0.5 (10.200.0.0/24) is on-link (within the same subnet) and therefore attempts ARP resolution for that IP on the local L2 rather than sending the packets to its configured gateway (10.2.1.1). ARP fails (no local host answers for 10.200.0.5 on that segment), so the host reports \"Destination Host Unreachable\" from itself. This explains why:\n  - pings from host_1_1_1_1 to web_server_2 work (other hosts with correct masks/gateway behavior route traffic via routers),\n  - router routing tables and OSPF are fine (packets routed correctly once they leave correctly-configured hosts),\n  - host_2_1_1_1 sees local ARP failure rather than routing failure.\n\nSupporting evidence (selected outputs)\n- host_2_1_1_1 ifconfig/ip: inet 10.2.1.2 netmask 255.0.0.0; default via 10.2.1.1\n- host_2_1_1_1 ping 10.200.0.5: \"From 10.2.1.2 icmp_seq=1 Destination Host Unreachable\" (host-generated).\n- router and OSPF: OSPF adjacencies Full and routes for 10.200.0.0/24 and 10.2.1.0/24 present across routers (examples shown in frr show ip route outputs).\n\nOther observations / notes\n- Inter-server (web_server_x to web_server_2) pings succeed; DNS server → web_server_2 succeeds, confirming the server farm and its local routing are healthy.\n- OSPF process outputs show expected numbers of LSAs and full neighbors. No router-level route blackholes or missing advertisements were observed in the captured routing tables.\n- Some of the earlier aggregated reachability entries were incomplete/unknown (not all pairwise tests ran to completion), but targeted tests and host config inspection provided the core diagnosis.\n\nConclusion (concise)\n- The network routing infrastructure (FRR/OSPF, routers, server access switch) is functioning correctly.\n- The outage/partial reachability is caused by misconfiguration at the host edge: host_2_1_1_1 has an incorrect netmask (255.0.0.0 instead of the intended 255.255.255.0), causing it to attempt to reach remote subnets directly on-link and fail (result: \"Destination Host Unreachable\").\n- Fault is localized to the host(s) with incorrect addressing; no evidence found of OSPF or router faults producing the observed symptom.\n\nIf you want, I can:\n- enumerate which other hosts show the same netmask (run get_host_net_config against other sample hosts), or\n- run ARP/trace tests from the affected host to demonstrate the ARP behavior, or\n- collect more router interface / ARP tables to further confirm L2 behavior.\n\n(Per your instruction, I have not included mitigation steps.)", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 15329, "output_tokens": 2810, "total_tokens": 18139, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 14080}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1152}}}
